{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582946"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:01:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:01:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1584"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1584","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1584"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,0.02,0.94,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1584"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79839"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1584","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1584"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1584"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65135"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"847"},{"type":"tags","id":"1803"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27270"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79839","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79839"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic after noticing redness in her right eye upon waking this morning. She denies eye pain, visual changes, discharge, or recent trauma. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her eye is inspected (Image). Visual acuity is 6/6 bilaterally. The remainder of the eye examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Conjunctivitis","Iritis","Scleritis","Subconjunctival haemorrhage","Episcleritis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image shows a classic presentation of \u003Cstrong\u003Esubconjunctival haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E, characterised by a well-demarcated area of bright red blood beneath the conjunctiva. The absence of pain, normal vision, and lack of other symptoms are typical features. Most cases are benign and self-limiting, resolving spontaneously within two to three weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConjunctivitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with bilateral redness, discharge (purulent in bacterial, watery in viral), and grittiness. The redness would be more diffuse rather than well-demarcated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIritis\u003C/strong\u003E (anterior uveitis) presents with pain, photophobia, and a circumcorneal injection pattern (perilimbal redness). Patients often have decreased vision and a constricted pupil.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScleritis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by severe, boring eye pain and a violaceous hue to the affected area. The inflammation is deeper, and the vessels have a characteristic \u0027lattice-like\u0027 pattern.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpiscleritis\u003C/strong\u003E presents with mild discomfort and sectoral redness that blanches with phenylephrine. The redness is more superficial and localised than in scleritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile most cases of subconjunctival haemorrhage are benign, assessment should include blood pressure measurement and review of anticoagulation in patients with risk factors. Management involves reassurance and explanation that the condition will resolve spontaneously.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Subconjunctival haemorrhage typically presents as a painless, well-demarcated area of bright red blood beneath the conjunctiva.","Most cases of subconjunctival haemorrhage are benign and self-limiting, requiring only reassurance.","Assessment of patients with subconjunctival haemorrhage should include review of any anticoagulation and blood pressure."],"references":["Cronau H. Kankanala RR, Mauger T. Diagnosis and Management of Red Eye in Primary Care. Am Fam Phys 2010; 81:137-44. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20082509/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65135"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1584"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18476"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18476","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18476"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/25a5d691-73e4-4c24-8804-6b51f308cf51.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/25a5d691-73e4-4c24-8804-6b51f308cf51.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":598}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65135","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65135"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-16T03:36:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-16T03:40:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1584"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79839"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d